dron</span><meta itemprop=3D"position" content=3D"4"></span></div><h1>Dodec=
ahedron</h1><p>A dodecahedron is a <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/polyhedr=
on">polyhedron</a> with 12 faces. In the figure below are 2 different types=
 of dodecahedrons. The prefix "dodeca" means twelve.</p>
<figure class=3D"imgalign">
	<img src=3D"https://www.math.net/img/a/geometry/shapes/dodecahedron/dodeca=
hedron.png" class=3D"scaleimg">
</figure>
<p>Because of their complex nature, a dodecahedron is a shape that is not c=
ommonly seen in everyday life.</p>

<h2>Properties of a regular dodecahedron</h2>
<p>A regular dodecahedron is a dodecahedron whose faces are all <a href=3D"=
https://www.math.net/congruent">congruent</a>, regular <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.math.net/polygon">polygons</a>. Otherwise, it is irregular. Regular dode=
cahedrons are studied more often.</p>
<figure class=3D"imgalign">
	<img src=3D"https://www.math.net/img/a/geometry/shapes/dodecahedron/dodeca=
hedron-names.png" class=3D"scaleimg">
</figure>
<p>A regular dodecahedron, such as the one shown above, has 12 congruent fa=
ces that are regular <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/pentagon">pentagons</a=
>, 30 congruent edges, and 20 vertices; an edge is a line segment formed by=
 the intersection of two adjacent faces; a vertex for a regular dodecahedro=
n is a point where 3 edges meet. Regular dodecahedrons are one of five Plat=
onic solids, which are a type of regular polyhedron.</p>

<h2>Surface area of a regular dodecahedron</h2>
<p>We can find the <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/area">area</a> of one of=
 the faces and multiply it by twelve to find the total surface area of a re=
gular dodecahedron.</p>
<p>A regular pentagon with side length, e (also the length of the edges of =
a regular dodecahedron), has an area, A, of</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/QSA9IFxmcmFje1xzc=
XJ0ezI1KzEwXHNxcnR7NX19fXs0fWVeMg=3D=3D_100.svg"></p>
<p>The total surface area, S, of a regular dodecahedron in terms of its edg=
es, e, is,</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img class=3D"scaleimg" src=3D"https://www.math.net/m=
j/UyA9MTIgXHRpbWVzIFxmcmFje1xzcXJ0ezI1KzEwXHNxcnR7NX19fXs0fWVeMiA9IDNcc3Fyd=
HsyNSsxMFxzcXJ0ezV9fWVeMg=3D=3D_100.svg"></p>

<h2>Volume of a regular dodecahedron</h2>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.math.net/volume">volume</a>, V, of regular do=
decahedron is</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/ViA9IFxmcmFjezE1K=
zdcc3FydHs1fX17NH1lXjM=3D_100.svg"></p>
<p>where e is the length of the edge of the regular dodecahedron.</p>

<div class=3D"examplep">
<p class=3D"example">Example:</p>
<p class=3D"question">If the total surface area of a regular dodecahedron i=
s 100, what is its volume?</p>
<p>We can find e by substituting the given value in for the total surface a=
rea to get</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/MTAwID0gM1xzcXJ0e=
zI1KzEwXHNxcnR7NX19ZV4y_100.svg"></p>
<p class=3D"imgalign">e =E2=89=88 4.84</p>
<p>Substituting the length of the edge into the volume formula:</p>
<p class=3D"imgalign"><img src=3D"https://www.math.net/mj/ViA9IFxmcmFjezE1K=
zdcc3FydHs1fX17NH0gXHRpbWVzIDQuODReMyBcYXBwcm94IDg2OC44NA=3D=3D_100.svg"></=
p>
